= doc_title(title: "Icons", comp: @comp) do |title|
  %p
    The
    %code loco_icon
    helper renders an inline SVG from any installed icon library. LocoMotion
    bundles Heroicons out of the box (the default), and you can add other
    libraries — Lucide, Phosphor, Tabler, brand sets, and more — by syncing them
    into your own application.

  %p
    Browse the bundled set at

    = succeed "." do
      = daisy_link("https://heroicons.com", target: "_blank", right_icon: "arrow-top-right-on-square", right_icon_css: "size-4")


= doc_example(title: "Basic Icons", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      By default, icons are displayed with the `size-5` Tailwind class to set the
      width and height. This can be overridden **without** using the
      `!` Tailwind modifier because we utilize the `:where()` pseudo-class to
      ensure that our default classes have the lowest CSS specificity possible.

      The icon color inherits the text color of the parent element.

      You can pass the icon as the first positional argument or via the `icon:`
      keyword argument.

  = loco_icon("academic-cap")
  = loco_icon(icon: "adjustments-horizontal")
  %span.text-blue-500
    = loco_icon("archive-box")


= doc_example(title: "Variants", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      Heroicons ships four variants. Choose one with the `variant:` option
      (`:outline` is the default); other libraries expose their own variants /
      weights the same way (e.g. Phosphor's `:thin` / `:bold` / `:duotone`).

  = loco_icon("bolt", variant: :outline, css: "size-8")
  = loco_icon("bolt", variant: :solid, css: "size-8")
  = loco_icon("bolt", variant: :mini, css: "size-5")
  = loco_icon("bolt", variant: :micro, css: "size-4")


= doc_example(title: "Customized Icons", example_css: "gap-x-2") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    %p
      You can customize the size, color, and other properties of the icons using
      standard Tailwind classes.

  = loco_icon("no-symbol", css: "size-4 text-red-600")
  = loco_icon("arrow-trending-up", css: "size-10 text-green-600")
  = loco_icon("exclamation-triangle", css: "size-14 text-yellow-400 animate-pulse")


= doc_example(title: "Other Libraries") do |doc|
  - doc.with_description do
    :markdown
      LocoMotion bundles only Heroicons to keep the gem small. To use another
      library, sync it into your app once and then pass `library:`:

      ```bash
      bin/rails loco_motion:icons:add lucide phosphor
      ```

      ```haml
      = loco_icon("heart", library: :lucide)
      = loco_icon("heart", library: :phosphor, variant: :duotone)
      ```

      The renderer checks your app's `app/assets/svg/icons` first, then falls
      back to the bundled icons — so synced libraries and per-icon overrides
      just work.
